{"parse":{"title":"Solar irradiance","pageid":1790,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>6-3-025</b>\n</p><p>Radiant power incident from the sun upon unit area of a receptor (e.<span class=\"mw-lingo-term\" data-lingo-term-id=\"b2f5ff47436671b6e533d8dc3614845d\">g</span>. a solar cell).\n</p><p><br>\nNote: 1 Solar irradiance may be direct irradiance or diffuse irradiance.\n</p><p><br>\nNote: 2 The solar irradiance depends on the geographical latitude, the season of the year and the time of the day, also on the intensity of solar emission and the transmission properties of the atmosphere, the value of air-mass and the inclination of the surface of the receptor.\n</p><p><br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<i>Please note that this is the term as it stands in the original <span class=\"mw-lingo-term\" data-lingo-term-id=\"0a1217bfe27a54fc7e55b72fc62c2371\">IALA</span> Dictionary edition (1970-1989)</i>\n<br>\n</p>\n<div class=\"LanguageLinks\">\n<table width=\"100%\">\n<tbody><tr valign=\"top\" style=\"background: #FFFFFF\">\n<td style=\"width: 25px; padding-left: 0em; border-right: 1px solid #aaaaaa;border-left: 1px solid #EEF3E2;border-top: 1px solid #EEF3E2;border-bottom: 1px solid #EEF3E2;\"><span typeof=\"mw:File\"><a href=\"/wiki/dictionary/index.php/File:25px-Geographylogo.png\" class=\"mw-file-description\" title=\"Languages\"><img alt=\"Languages\" src=\"/wiki/dictionary/images/8/82/25px-Geographylogo.png\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"25\" height=\"25\" class=\"mw-file-element\"></a></span></td>\n<td style=\"padding: 1px 1em 0; background: #EEF3E2;\">\n<p><b><a class=\"mw-selflink selflink\">English</a></b>\n<span></span>\n<span></span>\n<span></span>\n<span></span>\n</p>\n</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div><div class=\"mw-lingo-tooltip\" id=\"b2f5ff47436671b6e533d8dc3614845d\"><div class=\"mw-lingo-definition navigation-not-searchable\"><div class=\"mw-lingo-definition-text\">\n<p>acceleration due to gravity (m/s2)\n</p>\n</div></d